1. Import .csv data

Function for reading .csv files and writing it to just one .csv file

Function for reading all files with the required format (in this case mainly .csv) on a given path and writing all this data into one ‘all_in_one.csv’ file in the same folder.

The function also returns data from the resulting ‘all_in_one.csv’ file.

read_patients_data <- function(path, file_type) {
  list.files(path = path, 
             pattern = paste('*.', file_type, sep=''), 
             full.names = TRUE) %>% 
    map_df(~read_csv(., col_types = cols(.default = "c"))) %>% 
    distinct(.) %>% 
    write_csv(., paste(path, "all_in_one.csv", sep=''))
  
  return(read_csv(paste(path, "all_in_one.csv", sep='')))
}

We load data from all .csv files into one variable using the above function. In our case, the data is in the ‘./Data/’ folder.

There are 200 rows and 7 variables in the data.

5. An assumption about the difference between the number of days spent in hospital for female patients, that took in placebo and female patients who took drug type 2

Data extraction

At first, we extracted 2 vectors from our data frame:

days_females_placebo <- patients %>% 
  filter(gender=='female' & drug_type=='Placebo') %>%
  pull(days_in_hospital)
days_females_drug_2 <- patients %>% 
  filter(gender=='female' & drug_type=='New_type_2') %>%
  pull(days_in_hospital)

Normality check

In the subsequent stage we need to check the distribution for normality:

sh_placebo_5 <- shapiro.test(days_females_placebo)

W = 0.95885, p-value = 0.392042.

According to the Shapiro-Wilk normality test, we cannot reject the null hypothesis (the distribution is normal).

sh_drug2_5 <- shapiro.test(days_females_drug_2)

W = 0.899846, p-value = 0.018205.

According to the Shapiro-Wilk normality test the the distribution in the second group can be considered not normal (p-value = 0.0182 < 0.05, the difference is statistically significant).

Mann-Whitney U test

The distribution in the second group is not normal, therefore we decided to use nonparametric Mann-Whitney U test.

Firstly, we used two-sided t-test:

W = 497, p-value = 0.000221

The differences are statistically significant (p-value is below the chosen threshold of 0.05), therefore we can reject the null hypothesis (P(X > Y) = P(X < Y)) in favor of the alternative hypothesis (‘There is a statistically significant difference between the number of days spent in hospital for female patients, that took in placebo and female patients who took drug type 2’).

Then we used one-sided test:

W = 497, p-value = 0.00011

The differences are statistically significant (p-value is below the chosen threshold of 0.05), therefore we can reject the null hypothesis (P(X > Y) = P(X < Y)) in favor of the alternative hypothesis (‘The number of days spent in hospital for female patients, that took in placebo was greater, than for female patients who took drug type 2’).
